62 // Set some maximum limits on the size of the FSMs, in order to prevent runaway
63 // computation on pathological queries. As rough reference: As of 8.0.26,
64 // there is a single query in the test suite hitting these limits (it wants 8821
65 // NFSM states and an estimated 2^50 DFSM states). Excluding that query, the
66 // test suite contains the following largest FSMs:
67 //
68 // - Largest NFSM: 63 NFSM states => 2 DFSM states
69 // - Largest DFSM: 37 NFSM states => 152 DFSM states
70 //
71 // And for DBT-3:
72 //
73 // - Largest NFSM: 43 NFSM states => 3 DFSM states
74 // - Largest DFSM: 8 NFSM states => 8 DFSM states
75 //
76 // We could make system variables out of these if needed, but they would
77 // probably have to be settable by superusers only, in order to prevent runaway
78 // unabortable queries from taking down the server. Having them as fixed limits
79 // is good enough for now.
80 constexpr int kMaxNFSMStates = 200;
81 constexpr int kMaxDFSMStates = 2000;

808 /**
809 Do safe reduction on all orderings (some of them may get merged by
810 PruneUninterestingOrders() later), ie., remove all items that may be removed
811 using only FDs that always are active.
812
813 There's a problem in [Neu04] that is never adequately addressed; orderings are
814 only ever expanded, and then eventually compared against interesting orders.
815 But the interesting order itself is not necessarily extended, due to pruning.
816 For instance, if an index could yield (x,y) and we have {} → x, there's no way
817 we could get it to match the interesting order (y) even though they are
818 logically equivalent. For an even trickier case, imagine an index (x,y) and
819 an interesting order (y,z), with {} → x and y → z. For this to match, we'd
820 need to have a “super-order” (x,y,z) and infer that from both orderings.
821
822 Instead, we do a pre-step related to Simmen's “Test Ordering” procedure;
823 we reduce the orderings. In the example above, both will be reduced to (y),
824 and then match. This is mostly a band-aid around the problem; for instance,
825 it cannot deal with FDs that are not always active, and it does not deal

842 /**
843 We don't currently have any operators that only group and do not sort
844 (e.g. hash grouping), so we always implement grouping by sorting.
845 This function makes that representation explicit -- for each grouping,
846 it will make sure there is at least one ordering representing that
847 grouping. This means we never need to “sort by a grouping”, which
848 would destroy ordering information that could be useful later.
849
850 As an example, take SELECT ... GROUP BY a, b ORDER BY a. This needs to
851 group first by {a,b} (assume we're using filesort, not an index),
852 then sort by (a). If we just represent the sort we're doing as going
853 directly to {a,b}, we can't elide the sort on (a). Instead, we create
854 a sort (a,b) (implicitly convertible to {a,b}), which makes the FSM
855 understand that we're _both_ sorted on (a,b) and grouped on {a,b},
856 and then also sorted on (a).
857
858 Any given grouping would be satisfied by lots of different orderings:
859 {a,b} could be (a,b), (b,a), (a DESC, b) etc.. We look through all
860 interesting orders that are a subset of our grouping, and if they are,
861 we extend them arbitrarily to complete the grouping. E.g., if our
862 grouping is {a,b,c,d} and the ordering (c DESC, b) is interesting,
863 we make a homogenized ordering (c DESC, b, a, d). This is roughly
864 equivalent to Simmen's “Cover Order” procedure. If we cannot make
865 such a cover, we simply make a new last-resort ordering (a,b,c,d).
866
867 We don't consider equivalences here; perhaps we should, at least
868 for at-end groupings.
869 */

1688 /**
1689 From the NFSM, convert an equivalent DFSM.
1690
1691 This is by means of the so-called powerset conversion, which is more commonly
1692 used to convert NFAs to DFAs. (The only real difference is that FAs have
1693 accepting states, while our FSM instead needs to store information about
1694 constituent interesting order states.)
1695
1696 The powerset algorithm works by creating DFSM states that represent sets of
1697 NFSM states we could be in. E.g., if we have a state (a) and an FD {} → x can
1698 lead to new states () (ϵ-edge), (a) (implicit self-edge), (x), (ax), (xa),
1699 then we create a single new DFSM state that represent all those five states,
1700 and an {} → x edge from {(a)} to that new state. When creating edges from
1701 such superstates, we need to follow that FD from _all_ of them, so the list
1702 of constituent states can be fairly large.
1703
1704 In theory, we could get 2^n DFSM states from n NFSM states, but in practice,
1705 we get fewer since our orderings generally only increase, not decrease.
1706 We only generate DFSM states by following FDs from the initial NFSM state;
1707 we don't create states eagerly for all 2^n possibilities.
1708
1709 When creating DFSM states, we always include states that can be reached by
1710 means of always-active FDs. The ϵ edge (drop the last element from the
1711 ordering) is always active, and the client can also mark others as such.
1712 This means we get fewer DFSM states and fewer FDs to follow. See
1713 FunctionalDependency::always_active.
